## 4. MVP Definition

This case study was inspired by my own experience relocating within Spain and searching for housing in Barcelona as an immigrant.
During the apartment search process, I encountered a recurring challenge: most housing listings do not clearly indicate whether empadronamiento is allowed.
As a result, tenants must manually read listing descriptions, contact landlords, and often wait for responses that never arrive.
This problem is particularly critical for newcomers, since empadronamiento is required to access essential administrative services such as healthcare and residency procedures.

To define the MVP scope, different user segments affected by the housing search problem were analyzed and prioritized based on their needs and constraints.
The table below summarizes the main user personas identified during discovery.

### Persona Prioritization

Several user groups experience difficulties when searching for housing in Barcelona. However, their priorities differ depending on their administrative and housing constraints.

| Persona | Main Need | Pain Point | Constraint Type | Impact | Frequency | Priority |
|--------|-----------|------------|----------------|--------|-----------|----------|
| New immigrants / newcomers | Empadronamiento | Cannot access services without address registration | Administrative constraint | High | High | High |
| Freelancers | Flexible rental conditions | Lack of traditional work contracts | Financial constraint | Medium | Medium | Medium |
| International students | Temporary housing | High competition for rooms | Market constraint | Medium | High | Medium |
| Barcelona residents | Affordable housing | Rising prices and limited availability | Economic constraint | Medium | Medium | Low |

Personas were prioritized using an **Impact vs Frequency framework**, evaluating how strongly each problem affects users and how often it occurs during the housing search process.
The analysis shows that empadronamiento is not simply a housing preference but an administrative constraint that can block access to essential services.

For newcomers in Barcelona, this requirement makes empadronamiento compatibility one of the most critical factors when evaluating housing opportunities.
As a result, the MVP focuses on helping users identify listings where empadronamiento may be allowed.

### Market Behavior Insight

The lack of transparency around empadronamiento has also contributed to the emergence of informal arrangements within the housing search process.
In some cases, individuals may offer the possibility of registering an address separately from standard rental agreements, sometimes in exchange for a fee.

This behavior highlights how critical empadronamiento is for accessing administrative services and illustrates how users adapt when housing listings do not clearly communicate administrative compatibility.
These dynamics reinforce the importance of making empadronamiento information more transparent during the housing search process.

### 4.1 MVP Goal

The goal of the MVP is to help users quickly identify housing listings in Barcelona where empadronamiento may be allowed.
Instead of manually reading dozens of listing descriptions, users can receive filtered opportunities that match their administrative and housing needs.

### 4.2 MVP Features

The MVP focuses on a minimal set of features required to validate the concept.

Core features include:

• *User preference input*: Users provide basic housing preferences such as budget, accommodation type, and empadronamiento requirement.
• *Listing analysis*: The system analyzes housing listings from multiple platforms and social media sources.
• *Empadronamiento signal detection*: The AI agent scans listing descriptions and detects phrases indicating whether residency registration may be possible.
• *Basic listing information extraction*:  The system extracts relevant details such as price, location, and accommodation type.
• *Filtered housing opportunities*: The system returns listings where empadronamiento may be allowed.

### 4.3 Features Excluded from MVP

To keep the first version focused and simple, several features are intentionally excluded from the MVP.
The initial version prioritizes solving the core problem identified during discovery: helping users identify housing listings where empadronamiento may be allowed.

Therefore, features that improve communication, trust, or advanced ranking are considered secondary and will be explored in future iterations.

The following features are excluded from the MVP:

**Trust and verification**

• Scam detection  
• Landlord verification  

**Communication optimization**

• Automated landlord messaging  

**Advanced discovery features**

• Response probability prediction  
• Advanced opportunity ranking

### 4.4 Success Metrics

The success of the MVP will be evaluated by measuring whether users can more efficiently identify housing opportunities compatible with empadronamiento.

The primary success metric is the **reduction in time required to identify listings where empadronamiento may be allowed**.

| Metric Category | Metric | What it Measures |
|---|---|---|
| Discovery Efficiency | Time required to identify listings where empadronamiento may be allowed | Whether the product reduces search time during the housing discovery process |
| AI Performance | Accuracy of empadronamiento signal detection | Reliability of the AI analysis when detecting signals from listing descriptions |
| User Behavior | Number of listings users contact after using the system | Whether the surfaced opportunities are actionable and relevant |
| User Value | User-reported confidence during the housing search | Whether the product reduces uncertainty in the decision process |

These metrics help validate whether the system effectively reduces the time and uncertainty involved in identifying housing opportunities compatible with empadronamiento.
